  <content>
    <learning>
      <learningContent id="learncont-6ab651ff-c821-4a59-9c69-4037e66080bb">
        <title>Removing the Handlebar</title>
        <lcInstruction id="lci-69a14206-fb52-4573-9fa3-6279582132e5">
          <description>
            <warning>
              <warningAndCautionPara>Do not ride a bicycle with no grips on the handlebar. This can cause your hands to slip.</warningAndCautionPara>
            </warning>
            <para>In order to remove the handlebar, you must first remove any attachments. Begin by removing the grips. Place a long, thin screwdriver below the grip, and apply water between the grip and the handlebar. Turn the grip forward and backward to loosen, and then pull it off the end of the handlebar.</para>
            <para>Next, you need to remove the brake and the shift levers. To do this, loosen the clamp screw. The clamp screw can be found either behind or below the brake lever. Loosen the clamp screw with the Allen wrench, and remove the lever and the mount from the handlebar. Loosen the clamp bolt, and remove the shifter from the handlebar.</para>
            <figure>
              <title></title>
              <graphic infoEntityIdent="ICN-S1000DBIKE-AAA-DA22000-A-06RT9-00015-A-001-01" />
            </figure>
            <para>To remove the handlebar, use an Allen wrench to loosen the clamp bolt. Move the handlebar out of the stem.</para>
            <figure>
              <title></title>
              <graphic infoEntityIdent="ICN-S1000DBIKE-AAA-DA22000-A-06RT9-00016-A-001-01" />
            </figure>
          </description>
        </lcInstruction>
      </learningContent>
    </learning>
